0-81, 2004\u201305, 2008\u201309, 2009\u201310, 2012\u201313, 2017-18, 2018-19\n**Men's [[Cross country running|Cross Country]] {{small|(5)}} -  1983, 1985, 1994, 1996, 1997\n**Men's Outdoor [[Track & Field]] {{small|(3)}} -  1972, 1997, 1998\n**Men's [[association football|Soccer]] {{small|(2)}} -  2014, 2018\n*Women's sports (37):\n**Women's Basketball {{small|(19)}} -  1981-82, 1982\u201383, 1983\u201384, 1984\u201385, 1985\u201386, 1986\u201387, 1987\u201388, 1988\u201389, 1989\u201390, 1990\u201391, 1991\u201392, 1992\u201393, 1993\u201394, 1996\u201397, 1997\u201398, 1999\u201300, 2000\u201301, 2001\u201302, 2013\u201314\n**Women's [[association football|Soccer]] {{small|(2)}} -  1991, 1999\n**Women's [[Tennis]] {{small|(11)}} -  1983, 1985, 1987, 1990, 1991, 1992, 1993, 1994, 1997, 1998, 2003\n**Women's Outdoor Track & Field {{small|(2)}} - 1997, 1998\n**Women's [[Volleyball]] {{small|(3)}} -  1981, 1990, 2005\n\n===CCAA Tournament championships (18)===\nCal Poly Pomona has won CCAA tournament championships in the following events:\n\n*Men's sports (7):\n**Men's [[Baseball]] {{small|(2)}} -  2015, 2019\n**[[Cal Poly Pomona Broncos men's basketball|Men's Basketball]] {{small|(2)}} -  2013, 2015\n**Men's [[Soccer]] {{small|(3)}} -  2014, 2015, 2019\n*Women's sports (11):\n**Women's Basketball {{small|(11)}} -  1986, 1987, 1988, 1989, 1990, 1991, 1992, 1993, 1997, 1998, 2011\n\n==Olympics==\n\n===Olympic medalists===\n{{Dablink|See also: [[List of American universities with Olympic medals]]}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! width=140|Games\n!scope=\"col\" width:60px;\"|[[File:Gold medal.svg|20px]]\n!scope=\"col\" width:60px;\"|[[File:Silver medal.svg|20px]]\n!scope=\"col\" width:60px;\"|[[File:Bronze medal.svg|20px]]\n! width=55|Total\n|- align=center\n|align=left| [[Kim Rhode]] || 3 || 1 || 2 || '''6'''\n|- align=center\n|align=left| [[Chi Cheng (athlete)|Chi Cheng]] || 0 || 0 || 1 || '''1'''\n|- class=\"sortbottom\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| '''[[List of American universities with Olympic medals|Total]]''' ||bgcolor=gold|'''3''' ||bgcolor=silver|'''1''' ||bgcolor=#cc9966|'''3''' || '''7'''\n|}\n\n==Former sports==\n\n===Football===\nCal Poly Pomona fielded a [[college football]] team in Division II through the [[1982 Cal Poly Pomona Broncos football team|1982]] season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cal Poly Pomona drops football after 36 years|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=December 1, 1982|page=III-3|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9657762/cal_poly_pomona_drops_football/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|access-date=March 19, 2017}}{{Open access}}</ref><ref name=cpost13fb>{{cite news |url=http://www.thepolypost.com/news/cal-poly-pomona-s-football-past/article_e837fc7a-2586-11e3-b6f2-001a4bcf6878.html |work=Poly Post |location=(Pomona, California) |agency=(Cal Poly Pomona student newspaper) |last=Fogt |first=Anneli |title=Cal Poly's football past |date=September 24, 2013 |accessdate=January 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828090612/http://www.thepolypost.com/news/cal-poly-pomona-s-football-past/article_e837fc7a-2586-11e3-b6f2-001a4bcf6878.html |archive-date=August 28, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Jim Zorn]] was the Broncos' [[quarterback]] in [[1973 Cal Poly Pomona Broncos football team|1973]] and [[1974 Cal Poly Pomona Broncos football team|1974]]; he played in the [[National Football League|NFL]] for a decade, most notably as the starter for the expansion [[1976 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]].  \n{{Cal Poly Pomona Broncos football navbox}}\n<br>\n\n==Club sports==\nThere are currently 7 club sports at Cal Poly Pomona.<ref>{{cite web|last=Harper |first=Kyleena |url=http://collegeprowler.com/cal-poly-pomona/athletics/ |title=California State Polytechnic University - Pomona - Athletics - Niche |publisher=College Prowler |date= |accessdate=2014-08-27}}</ref>\n*[[cycling]]\n*[[equestrianism|equestrian]]\n*[[inline hockey]]\n*[[lacrosse]]\n*[[martial arts]]\n*ski and snowboard team\n*[[ultimate frisbee]]\nAll student may only participate in any clubs/activities with a 3.0 or higher\n\nPreviously, there was a Cal Poly Pomona Men's Club Volleyball team.  Team Coach was Coach Rosie Wegrich.\nPlayers:  Huey Long, Herwin Samson, Burton Pang, Matt Florido, Jonathan Cooper, Arnold Dichosa, Brian Bingman,\n\n==Bronco Pep Band==\n[[File:Bronco Pep Band CCAA 01.jpg|thumb|The Bronco Pep Band Victory Arc at the CCAA Division II Basketball Tournament]]\nThe Bronco Pep Band is a student-run band at the university. The band is currently a group within the Athletics Department.\n\nCal Poly Pomona music department student Daniel Sandt became the first director of what became known as \"Bronco Pep Band version 2.0\".<ref name=history>[http://www.cpp.edu/~pepband/history.html Bronco Pep Band History]</ref>\n\n===Directors===\n\n*Daniel Sandt (2002\u20132005) \n*Steven Corral (2005\u20132009) \n*James Rodriguez (2009-2012)\n*Branden Herron (2012-2014)\n*Ramiro Casta\u00f1eda (2014-2016)\n*Kingsley Hickman (2016-2018)<ref>{{cite web |title=Previous Directors |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~pepband/history/history_directors.html |website=Cal Poly Pomona - Bronco Pep Band |accessdate=28 February 2019}}</ref>\n*Viral Shukla (2018-present)<ref>{{cite web |title=The Band |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~pepband/officers.html |website=Cal Poly Pomona - Bronco Pep Band |accessdate=28 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Fight song==\n\n===The first fight song===\n'''Song of the Viking'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csupomona.edu/~library/specialcollections/voorhis/vikings/song.html |title=Special Collections & University Archives - Voorhis Vikings |publisher=Csupomona.edu |date=2012-01-10 |accessdate=2014-08-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140827153800/http://www.csupomona.edu/~library/specialcollections/voorhis/vikings/song.html# |archive-date=2014-08-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref><br/>\nWords by Jerry Voorhis, Sung to the tune of [[The Maine Stein Song]]\n\n===The new fight song===\n{{listen|filename=William Tell2.ogg|title=William Tell Overture|description=[[Cesare Sodero]]'s band performs part \n3 (Ranz des vaches)  of the overture in 1914.|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n'''Cal Poly Pomona Fight Song'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csupomona.edu/~pepband/music/index.html |title=Cal Poly Pomona - Bronco Pep Band |publisher=Csupomona.edu |accessdate=2014-08-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141103111840/http://www.csupomona.edu/~pepband/music/index.html# |archive-date=2014-11-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref><br/>\nWords sung to the trio section of John Phillip Sousa's Solid Men to the Front.\n\n===Unofficial Fight Song===\nThe  finale of the [[overture]] to the opera ''[[William Tell (opera)|William Tell]]'' has served as the university's fight song.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csupomona.edu/~pepband/history.html |title=Bronco Pep Band unofficial song |accessdate=2008-09-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705172519/http://www.csupomona.edu/~pepband/history.html# |archive-date=2008-07-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Cal Poly Pomona Broncos men's basketball]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.broncoathletics.com/}}\n\n{{California State Polytechnic University, Pomona}}\n{{California Collegiate Athletic Association navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Cal Poly Pomona Broncos|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|College sports team}}\n{{About||the athletic program at Cal Poly San Luis Obispo, California|Cal Poly Mustangs (San Luis Obispo)}}\n{{Infobox college athletics\n| name = Cal Poly Pomona Broncos\n| logo = Cal Poly Pomona Bronco Athletics Logo.png\n| logo_width = 250\n| university = [[California State Polytechnic University, Pomona]]\n| association = NCAA\n| conference = [[California Collegiate Athletic Association]]\n| division = [[NCAA Division II|Division II]]\n| director = Brian Swanson\n| location = [[Pomona, California|Pomona]], [[California]]\n| baseballfield = Scolinos Field <ref>[http://www.broncoathletics.com/sports/2010/10/19/Facilities.aspx]</ref> \n| basketballarena = Kellogg Arena\n| mascot = Billy Bronco\n| nickname = [[Broncos]]\n| fightsong = [[William Tell (opera)|William Tell Overture]]\n| pageurl = http://www.broncoathletics.com/\n}}\n\nThe '''Cal Poly Pomona Broncos''' or '''Cal Poly Broncos'''<ref>https://archive.is/20130409232009/http://polycentric.csupomona.edu/news_stories/2006/09/glenda-brock-honored-with-2006-hart-award.html</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Cal Poly Broncos Open '10 Season With Win Over SFU|url=http://boxscorenews.com/cal-poly-broncos-open-season-with-win-over-sfu-p1354-123.htm |accessdate=16 March 2013|newspaper=Stryker-Indigo}}</ref> are the athletic sports teams for the [[California State Polytechnic University, Pomona]] (Cal Poly Pomona).\n\nCal Poly Pomona has 11 varsity sports teams and offers student participation in a wide range of sports including [[association football|soccer]], [[volleyball]], [[track and field]], [[basketball]], and [[baseball]]. Cal Poly Pomona participates at the [[NCAA]]'s [[NCAA Division II|Division II]] (DII) level in the [[California Collegiate Athletic Association]] (CCAA). \n\nThe Broncos have 65 CCAA championships<ref>[http://goccaa.org/championships/All-Time_CCAA_List.pdf ''Accessed May 7th, 2015'']</ref> and 14 NCAA National Championships.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://goccaa.org/championships/ncaa_champions_from_the_ccaa |title=''Accessed May 7th, 2015'' |access-date=2015-05-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150510070933/http://www.goccaa.org/championships/ncaa_champions_from_the_ccaa |archive-date=2015-05-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Current and former Cal Poly athletes have won 7 Olympic medals ([[List of American universities with Olympic medals|3 gold, 1 silver, and 3 bronze]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cpp.edu/~75th/newsletter/athletics.shtml|title=Top 12 Athletics Achievements|website=www.cpp.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-02-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203075524/https://www.cpp.edu/~75th/newsletter/athletics.shtml#|archive-date=2017-02-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> As of 2019, Cal Poly ranks 9th in the nation in NCAA Division II [[Next College Student Athlete]] (NCSA) Power Rankings that calculate rankings based on NCSA recruiting network, general academic rankings by [[U.S. News & World Report]] Best Colleges, [[Integrated Postsecondary Education Data System]] (IPEDS) graduation rates and IPEDS average cost after aid.<ref>{{cite web |title=Best NCAA Division 2 Colleges |url=https://www.ncsasports.org/best-colleges/best-division-2-colleges |publisher=[[Next College Student Athlete]] |accessdate=7 October 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327092346/https://www.ncsasports.org/best-colleges/best-division-2-colleges |archivedate=March 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Teams==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; clear:right; margin:0 0 1em 1em;\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Cal Poly Pomona Broncos|Men's sports|Women's sports}}\n|-\n| Baseball || [[Cal Poly Pomona Broncos women's basketball|Basketball]]\n|-\n| [[Cal Poly Pomona Broncos men's basketball|Basketball]] || Cross country\n|-\n| Cross country || Soccer\n|-\n| Soccer || Track and field<sup>\u2020</sup>\n|-\n| Track and field<sup></sup> || Volleyball\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"{{NCAA secondary color cell|Cal Poly Pomona Broncos}}\" | {{small|\u2020 \u2013 Track and field includes both indoor and outdoor}}\n|}\n[[File:11-11-06-GalenCenter-inside.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Cal Poly Pomona's Men's Basketball Team playing against the [[USC Trojans men's basketball|USC Trojans]] at [[Galen Center]]]]\n\nWhile in existence, the Broncos' softball team appeared in seven [[Women's College World Series]], in 1978, 1979, 1980, 1984, 1985, 1988 and 1989.<ref name=\"Plummer\">{{cite book|title=A Series Of Their Own: History Of The Women's College World Series|first1=William |last1=Plummer|first2=Larry C.|last2=Floyd|year=2013|publisher= Turnkey Communications Inc.|location= Oklahoma City, Oklahoma, United States|isbn=978-0-9893007-0-4}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Championships==\n\n===Appearances===\n\nThe Cal Poly Pomona Broncos competed in the NCAA Tournament across 11 active sports (5 men's and 6 women's) 165 times at the Division II level.<ref>{{cite web|title=NCAA Championships Statistics|url=https://www.ncaa.org/championships/statistics|publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]|accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n<div class=\"messagebox\" style=\"inline: left; width: 98%; margin-left: 10px;\"><center>'''NCAA Tournament Appearances'''</center>'''Baseball (12)''': 1976 \u2022 1979 \u2022 1980 \u2022 1983 \u2022 1985 \u2022 1988 \u2022 1993 \u2022 2011 \u2022 2014 \u2022 2015 \u2022 2016 \u2022 2017<br>'''Men's basketball (13)''': 1962 \u2022 1964 \u2022 1976 \u2022 2003 \u2022 2004 \u2022 2005 \u2022 2007 \u2022 2009 \u2022 2010 \u2022 2013 \u2022 2015 \u2022 2016 \u2022 2018<br>'''Women's basketball (25)''': 1982 \u2022 1983 \u2022 1984 \u2022 1985 \u2022 1986 \u2022 1987 \u2022 1988 \u2022 1989 \u2022 1990 \u2022 1991 \u2022 1992 \u2022 1993 \u2022 1997 \u2022 1998 \u2022 1999 \u2022 2000 \u2022 2001 \u2022 2002 \u2022 2004 \u2022 2005 \u2022 2010 \u2022 2011 \u2022 2012 \u2022 2014 \u2022 2015<br>'''Men's cross country (20)''': 1967 \u2022 1983 \u2022 1984 \u2022 1985 \u2022 1986 \u2022 1988 \u2022 1990 \u2022 1992 \u2022 1994 \u2022 1996 \u2022 1997 \u2022 2003 \u2022 2004 \u2022 2005 \u2022 2006 \u2022 2013 \u2022 2014 \u2022 2015 \u2022 2016 \u2022 2018<br>'''Women's cross country (4)''': 1985 \u2022 2010 \u2022 2016 \u2022 2017<br>'''Men's soccer (5)''': 1998 \u2022 2015 \u2022 2016 \u2022 2017 \u2022 2018<br>'''Women's soccer (4)''': 1999 \u2022 2001 \u2022 2012 \u2022 2014<br>'''Women's indoor track and field: <br>'''Men's outdoor track and field (38)''': 1965 \u2022 1967 \u2022 1968 \u2022 1971 \u2022 1972 \u2022 1973 \u2022 1975