ersity Press |location=Oxford, England |isbn=978-0-19-727627-3 |title-link=Jami' al-Tawarikh }}\n* {{cite book |last=Rashid al-Din Tabib |title=The Successors of Genghis Khan (extracts from Jami' Al-Tawarikh) |series=[[UNESCO Collection of Representative Works]]: Persian heritage series |translator = John Andrew Boyle from the Persian |year=1971 |publisher=Columbia University Press |location=New York, NY |url = https://www.questia.com/PM.qst?a=o&d=109217551 |isbn = 978-0-231-03351-0 }}\n* {{cite book |title = The Secret History of the Mongols: A Mongolian Epic Chronicle of the Thirteenth Century [Yuan chao bi shi] |series=Brill's Inner Asian Library vol. 7 |translator = [[Igor de Rachewiltz]] |year=2004 |publisher=Brill |location= [[Leiden]], [[South Holland]]; Boston, MA |isbn = 978-90-04-13159-0\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links|v=no|voy=no|species=no|n=no|d=Q720|b=no}}\n* {{Britannica|229093|Genghis Khan (Mongol ruler)}}\n* {{In Our Time|Genghis Khan|b00773mr|Genghis_Khan}}\n*Welcome to [http://www.coldsiberia.org/ The Realm of the Mongols]\n*Parts of this biography were taken from the [http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/mntoc.html Area Handbook series at the Library of Congress]\n*[http://necrometrics.com/pre1700a.htm#Mongol Estimates of Mongol warfare casualties]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040813232348/http://www.isidore-of-seville.com/genghis/ Genghis Khan on the Web] (directory of some 250 resources)\n*[http://www.wdl.org/en/item/2378 The History of Genghizcan the Great, First Emperor of the Antient Moguls and Tartars]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2011/jan/26/genghis-khan-eco-warrior Why Genghis Khan was good for the planet]. ''[[The Guardian]].'' January 26, 2011.\n*[http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2014/03/140310-genghis-khan-mongols-mongolia-climate-change \"Genghis Khan's Secret Weapon Was Rain\"], ''[[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]]'', Roff Smith, March 10, 2014\n\n{{-}}\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou|[[Borjigin|House of Borjigin]] (1206\u20131635)||{{circa|1162}}||1227}}[[File:Borjigit 1.png|24px]]\n{{S-reg}}\n|-\n{{S-bef|before=[[Hotula Khan]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Khamag Mongol|''Khagan'' of Khamag Mongol]]|years=1189\u20131206}}\n{{S-non|reason=<span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">Khamag Mongol ended,<br />succeeded by [[Mongol Empire]]</span>}}\n|-\n{{S-new|reason=Mongol Empire established}}\n{{S-ttl|title=''[[Khagan]]'' of the [[Mongol Empire]]|years=1206\u20131227}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Tolui]]<br /><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">As regent</span>}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Khagans of Mongol Empire}}\n{{Mongol Empire}}\n{{Yuan Emperors}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Genghis Khan| ]]\n[[Category:1160s births]]\n[[Category:1227 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Khentii Province]]\n[[Category:Great Khans of the Mongol Empire]]\n[[Category:13th-century Mongol rulers]]\n[[Category:12th-century Mongol rulers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n[[Category:Deaths by horse-riding accident]]\n[[Category:Genocide perpetrators]]\n[[Category:Mongol Empire people]]\n[[Category:Medieval military leaders]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genghis_Khan"}
{"title_page": "John Sauven", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=December 2013}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n'''John Sauven''', (born in [[Ealing]], west London, on 6 September 1954) is a trained economist, environmentalist and executive director of [[Greenpeace]] UK since 2008. Before that he was the director responsible for Greenpeace communications and specialised on solutions and working with business. Sauven started working in a temporary position for Greenpeace in 1991 while waiting for a place at teacher training college. As director, Sauven has helped to shape Greenpeace UK's commitment to defend the natural world and promote peace by investigating, exposing himself and confronting environmental abuse, and championing environmentally responsible solutions.<ref name=\"Greenpeace UK: What we do\">{{cite web|url=http://www.greenpeace.org.uk/what-we-do|title=Greenpeace: What we do}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n\nJohn Sauven was educated at [[St Benedict's School, Ealing|St Benedict's School]], Ealing and trained as an economist at [[University of Cardiff]] graduating with a BSc (Econ).<ref name=\"John Sauven: 'I want to claim the arctic region for all of mankind'\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/environment/john-sauven-i-want-to-claim-the-arctic-region-for-all-of-mankind-2353171.html|title=John Sauven: 'I want to claim the arctic region for all of mankind'|publisher=The Independent|date=12 September 2011|accessdate=28 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nSauven actively campaigns to ban underground [[nuclear testing]] in the Pacific and campaigns against the [[UK Trident programme]], the United Kingdom's missile-based nuclear weapons programme.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}}\n\nHe campaigns to protect the temperate [[rainforests]] on the west coast of Canada, helping to save the [[Great Bear Rainforest]] in northwest Canada from commercial logging. It was a highly organised campaign, mostly fought in the marketplace between logging companies, timber traders and their retail customers in Europe and North America. It also involved pushing the industry as a whole to accept [[Forest Stewardship Council]] (FSC) certified products that guaranteed legal and sustainable products, now widely recognised in both the timber and paper sectors as the mark of sustainability.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}}\n\nSauven actively campaigns to halt the [[deforestation]] of the [[tropical rainforests]] of the [[Amazon Basin|Amazon]], by companies planting soya beans, having coordinated the international campaign to secure a moratorium on further destruction of the Amazon. This was achieved through bringing together a huge alliance of US and European multinationals along with Brazilian counterparts involved in the soya producing, commodity trading and food retailing sectors. It was one of Greenpeace's most successful campaigns to protect large areas of the world's last intact rainforests providing both climate and biodiversity protection. Similar tactics were used to direct campaigns to halt the deforestation of the forests of [[Democratic Republic of Congo]] and [[Indonesia]].{{citation needed|date=October 2013}}\n\nSauven helped to develop Greenpeace's \"Greenfreeze\" campaign (greenfreeze technology is now a global refrigeration industry standard utilising [[isobutane]] and [[propane]] as [[refrigerant]]s and [[cyclopentane]] for producing the insulating foam<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acr-news.com/are-our-fridges-safe |title=Are our fridges safe? |publisher=Acr-news.com |date=2009-08-21 |accessdate=2017-02-18}}</ref>) to protect the ozone layer from disappearing because of our use of CFCs and other ozone layer destroying chemicals. John also famously bought a plot of land in the path of the proposed Heathrow third runway.<ref name=\"Discussion Point, John Sauven\">{{cite web|url=http://www.discussion-point.com/AuthorPage/author/john-sauven|title=Discussion Point, John Sauven|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130418234306/http://www.discussion-point.com/AuthorPage/author/john-sauven|archivedate=18 April 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nCurrently he is helping to strategise action-led, non-violent initiatives to save the [[North Pole]] from [[Big Oil]]. Sauven advocates urgent action to protect the area of sea ice around the North Pole, which is currently not national territory, by designating the area a 'global commons', collectively owned by humanity under the auspices of the United Nations.\"<ref name=\"John Sauven: 'I want to claim the arctic region for all of mankind'\"/>\n\nIn specialising on solutions and working with business, Sauven is conscious that Greenpeace's ongoing work may win fewer headlines, but the effort to evolve new, more sustainable business models is where the future will be won or lost. This is particularly the case with climate change where cleaner, more efficient products, processes and ways of producing energy need to be brought to market by government regulation and company innovation.<ref name=\"Discussion Point, John Sauven\"/>\n\nAs well as his work with Greenpeace, Sauven has edited ''Sanity'', the magazine of the Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament, [[CND]].{{citation needed|date=October 2013}}\n\nSauven has collaborated on several award winning films with film director [[Julian Temple]] and film producer Eski Thomas, commissioning ''The Ancient Forests'' to which [[David Attenborough|Sir David Attenborough]], [[Ewan McGregor]] and [[Andy Serkis]] lent their talents.<ref name=\"Greenpeace's The Ancient Forests\">{{cite web|url=http://www.greenpeace.org.uk/forests/the-ancient-forests|title=Greenpeace's The Ancient Forests|access-date=29 September 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404075345/http://www.greenpeace.org.uk/forests/the-ancient-forests|archive-date=4 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, John became a board member of ''Videre Est Credere'' (Latin for \"to see is to believe\") a UK Human Rights Charity.<ref>UK Charity Commission, [http://apps.charitycommission.gov.uk/Showcharity/RegisterOfCharities/CharityWithPartB.aspx?RegisteredCharityNumber=1130375&SubsidiaryNumber=0 UK Charity Commission Report on Videre], UK Charity Commission, 20 August 2013</ref> Videre describes itself as \"give[ing] local activists the equipment, training and support needed to safely capture compelling video evidence of human rights violations. This captured footage is verified, analysed and then distributed to those who can create change.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.videreonline.org |title=Videre Est Credere &#124; Charity Organisation for Human Rights Issues and Human Rights Abuse |publisher=Videreonline.org |date= |accessdate=2017-02-18}}</ref> He participates alongside movie producers [[Uri Fruchtmann]], [[Terry Gilliam]] and music producer [[Brian Eno]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.videreonline.org/our-people-2/|title=Our People {{!}} VIDERE|website=www.videreonline.org|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==Personal==\n\nSauven lives in Crouch End, north London, and is married to Janet Convery, a campaigner at the charity [[Action Aid]]. He has two sons.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/profile/johnsauven John Sauven profile in ''The Guardian'']\n* [https://www.independent.co.uk/environment/john-sauven-i-want-to-claim-the-arctic-region-for-all-of-mankind-2353171.html John Sauven article in ''The Independent'']\n\n{{Greenpeace}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sauven, John}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:People from Ealing]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at St Benedict's School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Cardiff University]]\n[[Category:Environmentalists]]\n[[Category:People associated with Greenpeace]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=December 2013}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n'''John Sauven''', (born in [[Ealing]], west London, on 6 September 1954) is a trained economist, environmentalist and executive director of [[Greenpeace]] UK since 2008. Before that he was the director responsible for Greenpeace communications and specialised on solutions and working with business. Sauven started working in a temporary position for Greenpeace in 1991 while waiting for a place at teacher training college. As director, Sauven has helped to shape Greenpeace UK's commitment to defend the natural world and promote peace by investigating, exposing himself and confronting environmental abuse, and championing environmentally responsible solutions.<ref name=\"Greenpeace UK: What we do\">{{cite web|url=http://www.greenpeace.org.uk/what-we-do|title=Greenpeace: What we do}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n\nJohn Sauven was educated at [[St Benedict's School, Ealing|St Benedict's School]], Ealing and trained as an economist at [[University of Cardiff]] graduating with a BSc (Econ).<ref name=\"John Sauven: 'I want to claim the arctic region for all of mankind'\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/environment/john-sauven-i-want-to-claim-the-arctic-region-for-all-of-mankind-2353171.html|title=John Sauven: 'I want to claim the arctic region for all of mankind'|publisher=The Independent|date=12 September 2011|accessdate=28 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nSauven actively campaigns to ban underground [[nuclear testing]] in the Pacific and campaigns against the [[UK Trident programme]], the United Kingdom's missile-based nuclear weapons programme.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}}\n\nHe campaigns to protect the temperate [[rainforests]] on the west coast of Canada, helping to save the [[Great Bear Rainforest]] in northwest Canada from commercial logging. It was a highly organised campaign, mostly fought in the marketplace between logging companies, timber traders and their retail customers in Europe and North America. It also involved pushing the industry as a whole to accept [[Forest Stewardship Council]] (FSC) certified produc